[src:server-side-rendering-web/api-streams-api] This feature is well established and works across many devices and browser versions.
[src:server-side-rendering-web/api-streams-api] It’s been available across browsers since January 2019.
[src:server-side-rendering-web/api-streams-api] The Streams API allows JavaScript to programmatically access streams of data received over the network and process them as desired by the developer.
[src:server-side-rendering-web/api-streams-api] Streaming involves breaking a resource that you want to receive over a network down into small chunks, then processing it bit by bit.
[src:server-side-rendering-web/api-streams-api] Browsers already do this when receiving media assets — videos buffer and play as more of the content downloads, and sometimes you'll see images display gradually as more is loaded too.
[src:server-side-rendering-web/api-streams-api] But this capability has never been available to JavaScript before.
[src:server-side-rendering-web/api-streams-api] Previously, if we wanted to process a resource of some kind (video, text file, etc.), we'd have to download the entire file, wait for it to be deserialized into a suitable format, then process all the data.
[src:server-side-rendering-web/api-streams-api] With the Streams API, you can start processing raw data with JavaScript bit by bit, as soon as it is available, without needing to generate a buffer, string, or blob.
[src:server-side-rendering-web/api-streams-api] (The basic concept of the stream API is data is fetched from the network in several data packets.
[src:server-side-rendering-web/api-streams-api] There are more advantages too — you can detect when streams start or end, chain streams together, handle errors and cancel streams as required, and react to the speed at which the stream is being read.
[src:server-side-rendering-web/api-streams-api] The usage of Streams hinges on making responses available as streams.
[src:server-side-rendering-web/api-streams-api] For example, the response body returned by a successful fetch request is a `ReadableStream` that can be read by a reader created with `ReadableStream.getReader()`.
[src:server-side-rendering-web/api-streams-api] More complicated uses involve creating your own stream using the `ReadableStream()` constructor, for example to process data inside a service worker.
[src:server-side-rendering-web/api-streams-api] You can also write data to streams using `WritableStream`.
[src:server-side-rendering-web/api-streams-api] It can be used to handle response streams of the Fetch API, or developer-defined streams (e.g., a custom `ReadableStream()` constructor).
[src:server-side-rendering-web/api-streams-api] Represents a default reader that can be used to read stream data supplied from a network (e.g., a fetch request).
[src:server-side-rendering-web/api-streams-api] Represents a controller allowing control of a `ReadableStream`'s state and internal queue.
[src:server-side-rendering-web/api-streams-api] Default controllers are for streams that are not byte streams.
[src:server-side-rendering-web/api-streams-api] Provides a standard abstraction for writing streaming data to a destination, known as a sink.
[src:server-side-rendering-web/api-streams-api] This object comes with built-in backpressure and queuing.
[src:server-side-rendering-web/api-streams-api] Represents a default writable stream writer that can be used to write chunks of data to a writable stream.
[src:server-side-rendering-web/api-streams-api] Represents a controller allowing control of a `WritableStream`'s state.
[src:server-side-rendering-web/api-streams-api] When constructing a `WritableStream`, the underlying sink is given a corresponding `WritableStreamDefaultController` instance to manipulate.
[src:server-side-rendering-web/api-streams-api] Represents an abstraction for a stream object that transforms data as it passes through a pipe chain of stream objects.
[src:server-side-rendering-web/api-streams-api] Provides methods to manipulate the `ReadableStream` and `WritableStream` associated with a transform stream.
[src:server-side-rendering-web/api-streams-api] Provides a built-in byte length queuing strategy that can be used when constructing streams.
[src:server-side-rendering-web/api-streams-api] Provides a built-in chunk counting queuing strategy that can be used when constructing streams.
[src:server-side-rendering-web/api-streams-api] When a new `Request` object is constructed, you can pass it a `ReadableStream` in the `body` property of its `RequestInit` dictionary.
[src:server-side-rendering-web/api-streams-api] This `Request` could then be passed to a `fetch()` to commence fetching the stream.
[src:server-side-rendering-web/api-streams-api] The response body returned by a successful fetch request is exposed by default as a `ReadableStream`, and can have a reader attached to it, etc.
[src:server-side-rendering-web/api-streams-api] Represents a BYOB ("bring your own buffer") reader that can be used to read stream data supplied by the developer (e.g., a custom `ReadableStream()` constructor).
[src:server-side-rendering-web/api-streams-api] Byte stream controllers are for byte streams.
[src:server-side-rendering-web/api-streams-api] Represents a pull into request in a `ReadableByteStreamController`.
[src:server-side-rendering-web/api-streams-api] We have created a directory of examples to go along with the Streams API documentation — see mdn/dom-examples/streams.
[src:server-side-rendering-web/dynamic-web-page] A **dynamic web page** is a web page constructed at runtime (during software execution), as opposed to a *static web page*, delivered as it is stored.
[src:server-side-rendering-web/dynamic-web-page] A **server-side dynamic web page** is a web page whose construction is controlled by an application server processing server-side scripts.
[src:server-side-rendering-web/dynamic-web-page] In server-side scripting, parameters determine how the assembly of every new web page proceeds, and including the setting up of more client-side processing.
[src:server-side-rendering-web/dynamic-web-page] A **client-side dynamic web page** processes the web page using JavaScript running in the browser as it loads.
[src:server-side-rendering-web/dynamic-web-page] JavaScript can interact with the page via Document Object Model (DOM), to query page state and modify it.
[src:server-side-rendering-web/dynamic-web-page] Even though a web page can be dynamic on the client-side, it can still be hosted on a static hosting service such as GitHub Pages or Amazon S3 as long as there is not any server-side code included.
[src:server-side-rendering-web/dynamic-web-page] A dynamic web page is then reloaded by the user or by a computer program to change some variable content.
[src:server-side-rendering-web/dynamic-web-page] The updating information could come from the server, or from changes made to that page's DOM.
[src:server-side-rendering-web/dynamic-web-page] This may or may not truncate the browsing history or create a saved version to go back to, but a *dynamic web page update* using AJAX technologies will neither create a page to go back to, nor truncate the web browsing history forward of the displayed page.
[src:server-side-rendering-web/dynamic-web-page] Using AJAX, the end user gets one dynamic page managed as a single page in the web browser while the actual web content rendered on that page can vary.
[src:server-side-rendering-web/dynamic-web-page] The AJAX engine sits only on the browser requesting parts of its DOM, *the* DOM, for its client, from an application server.
[src:server-side-rendering-web/dynamic-web-page] A particular application server could offer a standardized REST style interface to offer services to the web application.
[src:server-side-rendering-web/dynamic-web-page] DHTML is the umbrella term for technologies and methods used to create web pages that are not static web pages, though it has fallen out of common use since the popularization of AJAX, a term which is now itself rarely used.
[src:server-side-rendering-web/dynamic-web-page] Client-side-scripting, server-side scripting, or a combination of these make for the dynamic web experience in a browser.
[src:server-side-rendering-web/dynamic-web-page] Classical hypertext navigation, with HTML or XHTML alone, provides "static" content, meaning that the user requests a web page and simply views the page and the information on that page.
[src:server-side-rendering-web/dynamic-web-page] However, a web page can also provide a "live", "dynamic", or "interactive" user experience.
[src:server-side-rendering-web/dynamic-web-page] Content (text, images, form fields, etc.) on a web page can change, in response to different contexts or conditions.
[src:server-side-rendering-web/dynamic-web-page] Web pages that use client-side scripting must use presentation technology broadly called rich interfaced pages.
[src:server-side-rendering-web/dynamic-web-page] Client-side scripting languages like JavaScript or ActionScript, used for Dynamic HTML (DHTML) and Flash technologies respectively, are frequently used to orchestrate media types (sound, animations, changing text, etc.) of the presentation.
[src:server-side-rendering-web/dynamic-web-page] The scripting also allows use of remote scripting, a technique by which the DHTML page requests additional information from a server, using a hidden Frame, XMLHttpRequests, or a web service.
[src:server-side-rendering-web/dynamic-web-page] It is also possible to use a web framework to create a web API, which the client, via the use of JavaScript, uses to obtain data and alter its appearance or behavior dynamically depending on the data.
[src:server-side-rendering-web/dynamic-web-page] Web pages that use server-side scripting are often created with the help of server-side languages such as PHP, Perl, ASP, JSP, ColdFusion and other languages.
[src:server-side-rendering-web/dynamic-web-page] These server-side languages typically use the Common Gateway Interface (CGI) to produce *dynamic web pages*.
[src:server-side-rendering-web/dynamic-web-page] These kinds of pages can also use, on the client-side, the first kind (DHTML, etc.).
[src:server-side-rendering-web/dynamic-web-page] It is difficult to be precise about "dynamic web page beginnings" or chronology because the precise concept makes sense only after the "widespread development of web pages".
[src:server-side-rendering-web/dynamic-web-page] HTTP has existed since 1989, HTML, publicly standardized since 1996.
[src:server-side-rendering-web/dynamic-web-page] The web browser's rise in popularity started with Mosaic in 1993.
[src:server-side-rendering-web/dynamic-web-page] Between 1995 and 1996, multiple dynamic web products were introduced to the market, including Coldfusion, WebObjects, PHP, and Active Server Pages.
[src:server-side-rendering-web/dynamic-web-page] The introduction of JavaScript (then known as LiveScript) enabled the production of client-side dynamic web pages, with JavaScript code executed in the client's browser.
[src:server-side-rendering-web/dynamic-web-page] The letter "J" in the term AJAX originally indicated the use of JavaScript, as well as XML.
[src:server-side-rendering-web/dynamic-web-page] With the rise of server side JavaScript processing, for example, Node.js, originally developed in 2009, JavaScript is also used to dynamically create pages on the server that are sent fully formed to clients.
[src:server-side-rendering-web/dynamic-web-page] MediaWiki, the content management system that powers Wikipedia, is an example for an originally server-side dynamic web page, interacted with through form submissions and URL parameters.
[src:server-side-rendering-web/dynamic-web-page] A program running on a web server is used to generate the web content on various web pages, manage user sessions, and control workflow.
[src:server-side-rendering-web/dynamic-web-page] Server responses may be determined by such conditions as data in a posted HTML form, parameters in the URL, the type of browser being used, the passage of time, or a database or server state.
[src:server-side-rendering-web/dynamic-web-page] Such web pages are often created with the help of server-side languages such as ASP, ColdFusion, Java, JavaScript, Perl, PHP, Ruby, Python, and other languages, by a **support server** that can run on the same hardware as the web server.
[src:server-side-rendering-web/dynamic-web-page] These server-side languages often use the Common Gateway Interface (CGI) to produce dynamic web pages.
[src:server-side-rendering-web/dynamic-web-page] Two notable exceptions are ASP.NET, and JSP, which reuse CGI concepts in their APIs but actually dispatch all web requests into a shared virtual machine.
[src:server-side-rendering-web/dynamic-web-page] The server-side languages are used to embed tags or markers within the source file of the web page on the web server.
[src:server-side-rendering-web/dynamic-web-page] When a user on a client computer requests that web page, the web server interprets these tags or markers to perform actions on the server.
[src:server-side-rendering-web/dynamic-web-page] For example, the server may be instructed to insert information from a database or information such as the current date.
[src:server-side-rendering-web/dynamic-web-page] Dynamic web pages are often cached when there are few or no changes expected and the page is anticipated to receive considerable amount of web traffic that would wastefully strain the server and slow down page loading if it had to generate the pages on the fly for each request.
[src:server-side-rendering-web/dynamic-web-page] Client-side scripting is changing interface behaviors within a specific web page in response to input device actions, or at specified timing events.
[src:server-side-rendering-web/dynamic-web-page] In this case, the dynamic behavior occurs within the presentation.
[src:server-side-rendering-web/dynamic-web-page] The client-side content is generated on the user's local computer system.
[src:server-side-rendering-web/dynamic-web-page] Such web pages use presentation technology called rich interfaced pages.
[src:server-side-rendering-web/dynamic-web-page] Client-side scripting also allows the use of remote scripting, a technique by which the DHTML page requests additional information from a server, using a hidden frame, XMLHttpRequests, or a Web service.
[src:server-side-rendering-web/dynamic-web-page] The first public use of JavaScript was in 1995, when the language was implemented in Netscape Navigator 2, standardized as ECMAScript two years later.
[src:server-side-rendering-web/dynamic-web-page] The client-side content is generated on the client's computer.
[src:server-side-rendering-web/dynamic-web-page] The web browser retrieves a page from the server, then processes the code embedded in the page (typically written in JavaScript) and displays the retrieved page's content to the user.
[src:server-side-rendering-web/dynamic-web-page] All of the client and server components that collectively build a dynamic web page are called a web application.
[src:server-side-rendering-web/dynamic-web-page] Web applications manage user interactions, state, security, and performance.
[src:server-side-rendering-web/dynamic-web-page] Ajax uses a combination of both client-side scripting and server-side requests.
[src:server-side-rendering-web/dynamic-web-page] It is a web application development technique for dynamically interchanging content, and it sends requests to the server for data in order to do so.
[src:server-side-rendering-web/dynamic-web-page] The server returns the requested data which is then processed by a client-side script.
[src:server-side-rendering-web/dynamic-web-page] This technique can reduce server load time because the client does not request the entire webpage to be regenerated by the server's language parser; only the content that will change is transmitted.
[src:server-side-rendering-web/dynamic-web-page] Google Maps is an example of a web application that uses Ajax techniques.
[src:server-side-rendering-web/dynamic-web-page] A web client, such as a web browser, can act as its own server, accessing data from many different servers, such as Gopher, FTP, NNTP (Usenet) and HTTP, to build a page.
[src:server-side-rendering-web/dynamic-web-page] HTTP supports uploading documents from the client back to the server.
[src:server-side-rendering-web/dynamic-web-page] There are several HTTP methods for doing this.
[src:server-side-rendering-web/glossary-ssr] A static site can be considered as SSR (and can be generated using SSR infrastructure), but there are nuanced differences.
[src:server-side-rendering-web/glossary-ssr] Content of a static site is generated at build time, not at request time.
[src:server-side-rendering-web/glossary-ssr] Static sites often do not need to be deployed on a server at all, and can be served from a CDN.
[src:server-side-rendering-web/glossary-ssr] The SSR/CSR distinction is more meaningful for sites with dynamic content, for example live-updating or user-specific content.
[src:server-side-rendering-web/glossary-ssr] In these cases, for every request, the server generates the HTML content on-the-fly because it is unrealistic to pregenerate every possible page.
[src:server-side-rendering-web/glossary-ssr] The HTML file contains near-complete page content, and any JavaScript asset is only to enable interactivity.
[src:server-side-rendering-web/glossary-ssr] Both SSR and CSR have their performance tradeoffs, and a mix of SSR and CSR can be used to combine the benefits of both techniques.
[src:server-side-rendering-web/glossary-ssr] For example, the server can generate a page skeleton with empty placeholders, and the client can fetch additional data and update the page as needed.
[src:server-side-rendering-web/guide-ajax] Another very common task in modern websites and applications is making network requests to retrieve individual data items from the server to update sections of a webpage without having to load an entire new page.
[src:server-side-rendering-web/guide-ajax] This seemingly small detail has had a huge impact on the performance and behavior of sites, so in this article, we'll explain the concept and look at technologies that make it possible: in particular, the Fetch API.
[src:server-side-rendering-web/guide-ajax] A web page consists of an HTML page and (usually) various other files, such as stylesheets, scripts, and images.
[src:server-side-rendering-web/guide-ajax] The basic model of page loading on the Web is that your browser makes one or more HTTP requests to the server for the files needed to display the page, and the server responds with the requested files.
[src:server-side-rendering-web/guide-ajax] If you visit another page, the browser requests the new files, and the server responds with them.
[src:server-side-rendering-web/guide-ajax] This model works perfectly well for many sites.
[src:server-side-rendering-web/guide-ajax] But consider a website that's very data-driven.
[src:server-side-rendering-web/guide-ajax] For example, a library website like the Vancouver Public Library.
[src:server-side-rendering-web/guide-ajax] Among other things you could think of a site like this as a user interface to a database.
[src:server-side-rendering-web/guide-ajax] It might let you search for a particular genre of book, or might show you recommendations for books you might like, based on books you've previously borrowed.
[src:server-side-rendering-web/guide-ajax] When you do this, it needs to update the page with the new set of books to display.
[src:server-side-rendering-web/guide-ajax] But note that most of the page content — including items like the page header, sidebar, and footer — stays the same.
[src:server-side-rendering-web/guide-ajax] The trouble with the traditional model here is that we'd have to fetch and load the entire page, even when we only need to update one part of it.
[src:server-side-rendering-web/guide-ajax] This is inefficient and can result in a poor user experience.
[src:server-side-rendering-web/guide-ajax] So instead of the traditional model, many websites use JavaScript APIs to request data from the server and update the page content without a page load.
[src:server-side-rendering-web/guide-ajax] So when the user searches for a new product, the browser only requests the data which is needed to update the page — the set of new books to display, for instance.
[src:server-side-rendering-web/guide-ajax] This enables JavaScript running in a page to make an HTTP request to a server to retrieve specific resources.
[src:server-side-rendering-web/guide-ajax] When the server provides them, the JavaScript can use the data to update the page, typically by using DOM manipulation APIs.
[src:server-side-rendering-web/guide-ajax] The data requested is often JSON, which is a good format for transferring structured data, but can also be HTML or just text.
[src:server-side-rendering-web/guide-ajax] This is a common pattern for data-driven sites such as Amazon, YouTube, eBay, and so on.
[src:server-side-rendering-web/guide-ajax] To speed things up even further, some sites also store assets and data on the user's computer when they are first requested, meaning that on subsequent visits they use the local versions instead of downloading fresh copies every time the page is first loaded.
[src:server-side-rendering-web/guide-ajax] The content is only reloaded from the server when it has been updated.
[src:server-side-rendering-web/guide-ajax] In this section we'll walk through a couple of examples of the Fetch API.
[src:server-side-rendering-web/guide-ajax] The examples below are of a certain level of complexity, and show how to use the Fetch API in some real world contexts.
[src:server-side-rendering-web/guide-ajax] If you have never used fetch before, you might want to start by working through Scrimba's First fetch *MDN learning partner* interactive tutorial, which provides a very simple intro walkthrough.
[src:server-side-rendering-web/guide-ajax] For this example, we'll request data out of a few different text files and use them to populate a content area.
[src:server-side-rendering-web/guide-ajax] This series of files will act as our fake database; in a real application, we'd be more likely to use a server-side language like PHP, Python, or Node to request our data from a database.
[src:server-side-rendering-web/guide-ajax] Here, however, we want to keep it simple and concentrate on the client-side part of this.
[src:server-side-rendering-web/guide-ajax] To begin this example, make a local copy of fetch-start.html and the four text files — verse1.txt, verse2.txt, verse3.txt, and verse4.txt — in a new directory on your computer.
[src:server-side-rendering-web/guide-ajax] In this example, we will fetch a different verse of the poem (which you may well recognize) when it's selected in the drop-down menu.
[src:server-side-rendering-web/guide-ajax] Just inside the `<script>` element, add the following code.
[src:server-side-rendering-web/guide-ajax] This stores references to the `<select>` and `<pre>` elements and adds a listener to the `<select>` element, so that when the user selects a new value, the new value is passed to the function named `updateDisplay()` as a parameter.
[src:server-side-rendering-web/guide-ajax] Let's define our `updateDisplay()` function.
[src:server-side-rendering-web/guide-ajax] First of all, put the following beneath your previous code block — this is the empty shell of the function.
[src:server-side-rendering-web/guide-ajax] We'll start our function by constructing a relative URL pointing to the text file we want to load, as we'll need it later.
[src:server-side-rendering-web/guide-ajax] The value of the `<select>` element at any time is the same as the text inside the selected `<option>` (unless you specify a different value in a value attribute) — so for example "Verse 1".
[src:server-side-rendering-web/guide-ajax] The corresponding verse text file is "verse1.txt", and is in the same directory as the HTML file, therefore just the file name will do.
[src:server-side-rendering-web/guide-ajax] However, web servers tend to be case-sensitive, and the file name doesn't have a space in it.
[src:server-side-rendering-web/guide-ajax] To convert "Verse 1" to "verse1.txt" we need to convert the 'V' to lower case, remove the space, and add ".txt" on the end.
[src:server-side-rendering-web/guide-ajax] This can be done with `replace()`, `toLowerCase()`, and template literal.
[src:server-side-rendering-web/guide-ajax] First, the entry point to the Fetch API is a global function called `fetch()`, that takes the URL as a parameter (it takes another optional parameter for custom settings, but we're not using that here).
[src:server-side-rendering-web/guide-ajax] Next, `fetch()` is an asynchronous API which returns a `Promise`.
[src:server-side-rendering-web/guide-ajax] If you don't know what that is, read the module on asynchronous JavaScript, and in particular the lesson on promises, then come back here.
[src:server-side-rendering-web/guide-ajax] You'll find that article also talks about the `fetch()` API!
[src:server-side-rendering-web/guide-ajax] So because `fetch()` returns a promise, we pass a function into the `then()` method of the returned promise.
[src:server-side-rendering-web/guide-ajax] This method will be called when the HTTP request has received a response from the server.
[src:server-side-rendering-web/guide-ajax] In the handler, we check that the request succeeded, and throw an error if it didn't.
[src:server-side-rendering-web/guide-ajax] Otherwise, we call `response.text()`, to get the response body as text.
[src:server-side-rendering-web/guide-ajax] It turns out that `response.text()` is *also* asynchronous, so we return the promise it returns, and pass a function into the `then()` method of this new promise.
[src:server-side-rendering-web/guide-ajax] This function will be called when the response text is ready, and inside it we will update our `<pre>` block with the text.
[src:server-side-rendering-web/guide-ajax] Finally, we chain a `catch()` handler at the end, to catch any errors thrown in either of the asynchronous functions we called or their handlers.
[src:server-side-rendering-web/guide-ajax] One problem with the example as it stands is that it won't show any of the poem when it first loads.
[src:server-side-rendering-web/guide-ajax] Modern browsers will not run HTTP requests if you just run the example from a local file.
[src:server-side-rendering-web/guide-ajax] This is because of security restrictions (for more on web security, read Website security).
[src:server-side-rendering-web/guide-ajax] To get around this, we need to test the example by running it through a local web server.
[src:server-side-rendering-web/guide-ajax] To find out how to do this, see How do you set up a local testing server?.
[src:server-side-rendering-web/guide-ajax] In this example we have created a sample site called The Can Store — it's a fictional supermarket that only sells canned goods.
[src:server-side-rendering-web/guide-ajax] You can find this example live on GitHub, and see the source code.
[src:server-side-rendering-web/guide-ajax] By default, the site displays all the products, but you can use the form controls in the left-hand column to filter them by category, or search term, or both.
[src:server-side-rendering-web/guide-ajax] There is quite a lot of complex code that deals with filtering the products by category and search terms, manipulating strings so the data displays correctly in the UI, etc.
[src:server-side-rendering-web/guide-ajax] We won't discuss all of it in the article, but you can find extensive comments in the code (see can-script.js).
[src:server-side-rendering-web/guide-ajax] We will, however, explain the Fetch code.
[src:server-side-rendering-web/guide-ajax] The `fetch()` function returns a promise.
[src:server-side-rendering-web/guide-ajax] If this completes successfully, the function inside the first `.then()` block contains the `response` returned from the network.
[src:server-side-rendering-web/guide-ajax] Next we pass a function into the `then()` method of that returned promise.
[src:server-side-rendering-web/guide-ajax] This function will be passed an object containing the response data as JSON, which we pass into the `initialize()` function.
[src:server-side-rendering-web/guide-ajax] It is `initialize()` which starts the process of displaying all the products in the user interface.
[src:server-side-rendering-web/guide-ajax] To handle errors, we chain a `.catch()` block onto the end of the chain.
[src:server-side-rendering-web/guide-ajax] This runs if the promise fails for some reason.
[src:server-side-rendering-web/guide-ajax] Inside it, we include a function that is passed as a parameter, an `err` object.
[src:server-side-rendering-web/guide-ajax] This `err` object can be used to report the nature of the error that has occurred, in this case we do it with a simple `console.error()`.
[src:server-side-rendering-web/guide-ajax] However, a complete website would handle this error more gracefully by displaying a message on the user's screen and perhaps offering options to remedy the situation, but we don't need anything more than a simple `console.error()`.
[src:server-side-rendering-web/guide-ajax] Run the code through a web server (as described above, in Serving your example from a server).
[src:server-side-rendering-web/guide-ajax] Modify the path to the file being fetched, to something like 'produc.json' (make sure it is misspelled).
[src:server-side-rendering-web/guide-ajax] Now load the index file in your browser (via `localhost:8000`) and look in your browser developer console.
[src:server-side-rendering-web/guide-ajax] You'll see a message similar to "Fetch problem: HTTP error: 404".
[src:server-side-rendering-web/guide-ajax] This works in much the same way as the previous one, except that instead of using `json()`, we use `blob()`.
[src:server-side-rendering-web/guide-ajax] In this case we want to return our response as an image file, and the data format we use for that is Blob (the term is an abbreviation of "Binary Large Object" and can basically be used to represent large file-like objects, such as images or video files).
[src:server-side-rendering-web/guide-ajax] Once we've successfully received our blob, we pass it into our `showProduct()` function, which displays it.
[src:server-side-rendering-web/guide-ajax] Sometimes, especially in older code, you'll see another API called `XMLHttpRequest` (often abbreviated as "XHR") used to make HTTP requests.
[src:server-side-rendering-web/guide-ajax] This predated Fetch, and was really the first API widely used to implement AJAX.
[src:server-side-rendering-web/guide-ajax] We recommend you use Fetch if you can: it's a simpler API and has more features than `XMLHttpRequest`.
[src:server-side-rendering-web/guide-ajax] Call its `open()` method to initialize it.
[src:server-side-rendering-web/guide-ajax] Add an event listener to its `load` event, which fires when the response has completed successfully.
[src:server-side-rendering-web/guide-ajax] In the listener we call `initialize()` with the data.
[src:server-side-rendering-web/guide-ajax] We also have to wrap the whole thing in the try...catch block, to handle any errors thrown by `open()` or `send()`.
[src:server-side-rendering-web/guide-ajax] Hopefully you think the Fetch API is an improvement over this.
[src:server-side-rendering-web/guide-ajax] In particular, see how we have to handle errors in two different places.
[src:server-side-rendering-web/guide-ajax] This article shows how to start working with Fetch to fetch data from the server.
[src:server-side-rendering-web/hydration-web-development] Frameworks that use hydration include Next.js and Nuxt.
[src:server-side-rendering-web/hydration-web-development] React v16.0 introduced a "hydrate" function, which hydrates an element, in its API.
[src:server-side-rendering-web/hydration-web-development] In *progressive rehydration*, individual pieces of a server-rendered application are “booted up” over time, rather than the current common approach of initializing the entire application at once.
[src:server-side-rendering-web/hydration-web-development] This can help reduce the amount of JavaScript required to make pages interactive, since client-side upgrading of low priority parts of the page can be deferred to prevent blocking the main thread.
[src:server-side-rendering-web/hydration-web-development] One framework that supports partial rehydration is Elder.js, which is based on Svelte.
[src:server-side-rendering-web/server-side-scripting] Server-side scripting is often used to provide a customized interface for the user.
[src:server-side-rendering-web/server-side-scripting] These scripts may assemble client characteristics for use in customizing the response based on those characteristics, the user's requirements, access rights, etc.
[src:server-side-rendering-web/server-side-scripting] Server-side scripting also enables the website owner to hide the source code that generates the interface, whereas, with client-side scripting, the user has access to all the code received by the client.
[src:server-side-rendering-web/server-side-scripting] A downside to the use of server-side scripting is that the client needs to make further requests over the network to the server in order to show new information to the user via the web browser.
[src:server-side-rendering-web/server-side-scripting] These requests can slow down the experience for the user, place more load on the server, and prevent the use of the application when the user is disconnected from the server.
[src:server-side-rendering-web/server-side-scripting] When the server serves data in a commonly used manner, for example, according to the HTTP or FTP protocols, users may have their choice of a number of client programs (most modern web browsers can request and receive data using both of those protocols).
[src:server-side-rendering-web/server-side-scripting] In the case of more specialized applications, programmers may write their own server, client, and communications protocol, that can only be used with one another.
[src:server-side-rendering-web/server-side-scripting] Programs that run on a user's local computer without ever sending or receiving data over a network are not considered clients, and so the operations of such programs would not be considered client-side operations.
[src:server-side-rendering-web/server-side-scripting] Netscape introduced an implementation of JavaScript for server-side scripting with Netscape Enterprise Server, first released in December, 1994 (soon after releasing JavaScript for browsers).
[src:server-side-rendering-web/server-side-scripting] Server-side scripting was later used in early 1996 by Fred Dufresne while developing the first website for Boston, MA television station WCVB.
[src:server-side-rendering-web/server-side-scripting] The technology is described in US patent 5835712 Archived 2020-02-25 at the Wayback Machine.
[src:server-side-rendering-web/server-side-scripting] The patent was issued in 1998 and is now owned by Open Invention Network (OIN).
[src:server-side-rendering-web/server-side-scripting] In 2010, OIN named Fred DuFresne a "Distinguished Inventor" for his work on server-side scripting.
[src:server-side-rendering-web/server-side-scripting] In the earlier days of the web, server-side scripting was almost exclusively performed by using a combination of C programs, Perl scripts, and shell scripts using the Common Gateway Interface (CGI).
[src:server-side-rendering-web/server-side-scripting] Those scripts were executed by the operating system, and the results were served back by the web server.
[src:server-side-rendering-web/server-side-scripting] Many modern web servers can directly execute on-line scripting languages such as ASP, JSP, Perl, PHP and Ruby either by the web server itself or via extension modules (e.g. mod_perl or mod_php) to the webserver.
[src:server-side-rendering-web/server-side-scripting] For example, WebDNA includes its own embedded database system.
[src:server-side-rendering-web/server-side-scripting] Either form of scripting (i.e., CGI or direct execution) can be used to build up complex multi-page sites, but direct execution usually results in less overhead because of the lower number of calls to external interpreters.
[src:server-side-rendering-web/server-side-scripting] Dynamic websites sometimes use custom web application servers, such as Glassfish, Plack and Python's "Base HTTP Server" library, although some may not consider this to be server-side scripting.
[src:server-side-rendering-web/server-side-scripting] When using dynamic web-based scripting techniques, developers must have a keen understanding of the logical, temporal, and physical separation between the client and the server.
[src:server-side-rendering-web/server-side-scripting] For a user's action to trigger the execution of server-side code, for example, a developer working with classic ASP must explicitly cause the user's browser to make a request back to the webserver.
[src:server-side-rendering-web/server-side-scripting] Server-side scripts are completely processed by the servers instead of clients.
[src:server-side-rendering-web/server-side-scripting] When clients request a page containing server-side scripts, the application server processes the scripts and returns an HTML page to the client.
[src:server-side-rendering-web/server-side-scripting] With the advent of single-page applications, an updated approach to server-side scripting was introduced, known as server-side rendering.
[src:server-side-rendering-web/server-side-scripting] With server-side rendering, static HTML can be sent from the server to the client, and client-side JavaScript then makes the web page dynamic by attaching event handlers to the HTML elements in a process called hydration.
[src:server-side-rendering-web/server-side-scripting] Examples of frameworks that support server-side rendering are Next.js, Nuxt.js, Angular.
[src:server-side-rendering-web/server-side-scripting] An alternative to server-side rendering is static site generation.
[src:server-side-rendering-web/server-side-scripting] With server-side rendering, the page is generally assembled on the server once per each request.
[src:server-side-rendering-web/server-side-scripting] By contrast, with static site generation, the application generates all the static HTML pages at build time.
[src:server-side-rendering-web/server-side-scripting] These pre-built pages are then sent to the client at each request, without having to build them again.
[src:server-side-rendering-web/server-side-scripting] This leads to faster rendering times, since a new page doesn't have to be generated on every request; the server simply hands over a file it already generated in the past.
[src:server-side-rendering-web/server-side-scripting] The downside is that when some data on the page changes, it needs to be rebuilt.
[src:server-side-rendering-web/server-side-scripting] Examples of static site generation tools are Jekyll and Gatsby.
[src:server-side-rendering-web/server-side-scripting] Sites generated by static site generation tools are often hosted on Netlify, Vercel or GitHub pages.
